			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'm wondering something... The numbers of  PRG banks must be a power of two; more generally, the number of bytes must be a power of two.
<br />
<br />I think that would be sensible that instead of numbering the number of 16K PRG banks, it could be... a power of two of the numbers of bytes of PRG. So if there's 2 x 16K PRG, the number should be 15, 2^15 = 32K. So, using this system, we can define both insanely small and insanely big PRG sizes; to specify a PRG of 16 bytes (why? Memblers may answer...) the number should be 4. For a 8Mbyte game (why this?!) the number should be 23, 2^23 = 8M. The problem is, there should be a limit for this number, because even with only 5 bits we can specify a 2GB PRG size — waaayyyyy too much. But he main advantage is that we can make both very small and very huge PRG ROM.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
